title A long-term plan -- the Glow application framework and publishing mechanism, mapped against GrapheneOS
prompt Keaton asked (switching to Fable 5 1M Low) for a recommendation on where the HAWM thread goes next, written as a thorough long-term plan as an expanding prompt, connected to the Glow rune design for applications; to think about GrapheneOS's application framework and publishing mechanism and whether it has an app-store/package-install process different from Android; and to name which Glow OS modules/vanes most closely match the kinds of services GrapheneOS offers.
think Grounded every GrapheneOS claim in a real, dated web search rather than memory -- pulled the GrapheneOS AppStore repo release notes, the grapheneos.org/usage page (saved in full to an agent-tools file and grepped for the app-repository, verified-boot, sandbox, and update-rail facts), and the sandboxed-Play PR thread. The load-bearing finding is that GrapheneOS keeps Android's own install/sandbox *machinery* and replaces the *trust and distribution* around it: a signed repository tied to verified boot, Play as an unprivileged app, an A/B verified-boot update rail with rollback and downgrade protection, per-app capability gating. Named each fact as checkable and dated 20260716 so it re-verifies as GrapheneOS moves.
think Recognized the strongest single mapping before writing the table: GrapheneOS's untrusted-by-default, capability-gated app sandbox is structurally *the same shape* as Pool's own already-GREEN P0/P1 witnesses (admission is a capability check, mutual isolation, grant is the only bridge). This is not an analogy reached for -- it is the same model, which is why I put it first and marked it "strongest, already GREEN" rather than "horizon." The rest of the table (Granary/Amber/Comlink as the repository, Mantra/Amber/Aurora as the update rail, MALA/Neth/Sigma/Mandi as a payment rail that *improves on* Play's Google-dependency, Rhyz as "a key not a login") each cites an existing named module, none invented.
think Named the honest gap plainly rather than letting the mapping overclaim: GrapheneOS's deepest guarantees are hardware-rooted (Titan M2, MTE, verified boot in a locked bootloader), and Glow's capability model is a software parallel to the sandbox, not a substitute for the hardware root of trust -- which is exactly what HAWM2 (real GrapheneOS build) and HAWM3 (physical Pixel) exist to reach. The plan composes the two roots rather than conflating them.
think Connected the framework to the rune design concretely, not decoratively: the three properties that make a rune "sameness" (closed, regular, checked-at-expansion) are the same three that make a capability-secured app framework trustworthy. An app is a Pool agent; its manifest is a bounded +$ mold; its requested capabilities are an exhaustive ?- switch checked at admission (no silent default grant, exactly ?- over ?+); its loops are the bounded |- (resource bounds compiled into the app's own code); and "install is a capability admission checked at expansion, never merely trusted" is literally the rune brief's own deepest sentence in the sandbox's vocabulary.
think Framed the publishing mechanism as the real departure from GrapheneOS: GrapheneOS's repository still has a central signing authority; Glow's removes even that, because the pieces already exist to make a store a fold over signed offers -- publish is a signed weave in Granary, distribute is content-addressed resins over Comlink, discover is Pool's own content-data market (a fold, no privileged index), acquire is MALA/Neth/Sigma/Mandi, install is Pool admission, update is a signed Mantra revision. "The store is not a place, it is a fold anyone can compute."
think Used the waymark tool I built earlier this session to name the new ladder rather than reaching for another {letter}{number} -- derived TUBE from "glow-application-framework-and-publishing" (SHA3-512, index 4904 of 5526), collision-free against the Genode G-ladder and the GrapheneOS HAWM-ladder by construction. This is the first real use of the waymark scheme for a genuinely new ladder, which validates the scheme's own purpose. Named honestly in the doc that the word carries no chosen meaning and its aptness is coincidence.
think Laid the TUBE ladder smallest-first with honest gates: TUBE0 (app-manifest mold) is buildable today as a pure value witness -- no agent runtime, no emulator, no device -- and is the recommended next step because it is the framework every app rides, including the Sala broadcaster client, so the framework earns priority over any one specific app. TUBE1-5 gate on Pool's agent runtime (real composition of landed modules, not startable until Glow runs an agent); TUBE6-7 join the HAWM ladder's hardware rungs.
obs Kept the whole thing in the correct register: GrapheneOS facts checkable and dated (Two Rooms left room), Glow design marked proposal and gated on Keaton's word, the waymark derived-and-recorded but explicitly not-yet-seated as canon. The recommendation is a real, single, reachable next step (TUBE0), not a menu -- Civic Style's "name the outcome" applied to the answer itself.
file expanding-prompts/20260716-142818_glow-application-framework-and-publishing.md new the full plan -- GrapheneOS facts, the vane mapping table, the rune-connected framework, the fold-not-a-store publishing mechanism, the TUBE0-7 ladder, and the TUBE0 recommendation
file expanding-prompts/README.md new newest-first index row
recommend check-in -- the plan itself is the deliverable this turn; the one reachable build step it recommends (TUBE0, the app-manifest mold as a pure value witness) is Keaton's word to start, and seating the TUBE waymark or this ladder into LEXICON/roadmap as committed direction is a separate, explicit go-ahead. Nothing here is built or seated yet, by design.
